  "doc_id": "5990",
  "text": "A novel arterivirus was recently discovered in a forest giant pouched rat (Cricetomys emini Wroughton, 1910) in Cameroon (GenBank and Ng et al., unpublished). In 2012, Dunowska et al. published the partial genome of a novel arterivirus-like pathogen, wobbly possum disease virus (WPDV), found in common brushtails (Diprodontia: Phalangeridae: Trichosurus vulpecula Kerr, 1972), a marsupial introduced to New Zealand [CITATION_1] . The complete genomic sequences of WPDV were deposited in GenBank [unpublished data], and the virus was isolated in tissue culture in 2015 [CITATION_2] . Both the virus from the forest giant pouched rat and WPDV genomes contain all arterivirus-defining elements described above, and recent electron-microscopic studies revealed that the WPDV particles assume the typical arterivirion shape (spherical to icosahedral particles) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . However, the WPDV genome sequence is highly divergent from the genomes of classified arteriviruses [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] , and WPDV is the first arterivirus found in a noneutherian host.",
